If you wanted a more general form, say `perceiveFormalChargeFromValence()` it might make sense here .. check for both cations and anions .. something like `mdlvalence_p.h` but inverted - formal charges from the bond order.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 3, 9, 22, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ghutchis', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 823164304, 'comment_body': 'We should also make sure the formal charge is written on save for CML files.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 3, 9, 22, 53, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ghutchis', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 823947915, 'comment_body': "You're right about `pdbformat`, this should probably be moved there...

Some form of `perceiveFormalChargeFromValence` would be useful for other formats, but unfortunately if it relies on valences, and depending on the method, it could only work on molecules where all hydrogens are explicit (i.e. no PDB); the implementation in this PR is restricted to checking fully substituted group 15/16 monocations because they are basically guaranteed to not be hydrogen-bound, however I don't see a clear path to a generalized method... I'll need to do more research around that, I admit I didn't consider more general options; maybe we can eventually find a heuristic that correctly predicts most cases. Or implement both and move this smaller method into the PDB code (and XYZ too?).

And regarding anions... I believe some anions do fulfill the requirements this simpler method relies on (tetrafluoro- and tetrahydroxy- borates, aluminates and beryllates). I don't know much about them, or exactly what other such compounds are even possible. I know they have strongly electron-withdrawing substituents rather than organic radicals, and beryllium in beryllates is 4-substituted and has a -2 charge, which is outside the MDL valence model... I've never heard of other such ions involving heavier elements (too metallic?), or less electronegative substituents, but I'd need to consider the possibilities carefully.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 3, 10, 17, 0, 52, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'aerkiaga', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 823950702, 'comment_body': "I'll work on that too. I'll likely have some time later today.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 3, 10, 17, 3, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'aerkiaga', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 824132420, 'comment_body': 'This shouldn't be needed, since it's an integer. We ran into problems with CML expecting the "C" locale and floats written as "1,0456"', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 3, 10, 20, 33, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ghutchis', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 824326546, 'comment_body': "While this works, we should omit cases in which the formal charge is zero .. for something huge, it's just going to add a lot of extra text:

